s canon. It broadens the focus of living forms to include animated, creaturely, corporeal and Gothic bodies, exploring the way that Burton celebrates the body – whether human, animal, animated or anthropomorphised.In prioritising the somatic aspects of characters, Tim Burton’s Bodies spotlights actual physical attributes and behaviour, and considers what meanings these may impart in terms of race, class, gender, sexuality, humanimality and disability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aHuman body in motion pictures. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / Direction & Production.2bisacsh1 aBassil-Morozow, Helena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyacıoğlu, Elif, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClaire, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCobb, Thomas J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColombani, Elsa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Cath, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuarte, José, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeal, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHackett, Alexandra Jayne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHockenhull, Stella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolliday, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipiner, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiénard-Yeterian, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLloyd, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMantell,